This service runs in Kubernetes production environments.

## Deployment posture
- Target current stable Kubernetes behavior only.
- Do not rely on alpha or preview Kubernetes features unless explicitly requested.
- Prefer standard, broadly-supported primitives over clever manifest tricks.
- Keep manifests explicit, reviewable, and reversible.

## Workload choice
- Use Deployment for stateless application services unless there is a clear reason to use another controller.
- Use rolling updates intentionally.
- Avoid update strategies that risk unnecessary downtime.

## Probes
- Define readiness probes for traffic gating.
- Define liveness probes only when they truly detect unrecoverable failure.
- Define startup probes for slow-starting services so liveness/readiness do not cause premature restarts.
- Probe endpoints must reflect real application state, not just "process is alive".
- Readiness must fail when the service cannot safely serve traffic.

## Graceful shutdown
- Support graceful termination in the application.
- Respect SIGTERM and stop accepting new work promptly.
- Allow in-flight requests and background work to drain within the termination window.
- Do not rely on abrupt process termination as a normal shutdown mechanism.
- Keep Kubernetes termination settings aligned with application shutdown behavior.

## Resources
- Set CPU and memory requests and limits intentionally.
- Do not omit requests for production workloads.
- Size resources based on measurement, not guesswork.
- Avoid memory limits that are unrealistically close to normal steady-state usage.
- Revisit resource settings when major code-paths or traffic patterns change.

## Availability
- Use at least two replicas for production services when the system requires high availability.
- Use PodDisruptionBudget where service availability matters during voluntary disruptions.
- Use topology spread constraints or other scheduling controls to reduce correlated failure risk.
- Do not assume all replicas will land in safe failure domains by default.

## Security
- Use a dedicated ServiceAccount only when needed.
- Do not grant broad Kubernetes API permissions without a clear requirement.
- Run containers with a restrictive security posture.
- Prefer non-root execution where supported by the image and application.
- Avoid privileged containers, host networking, host PID, and hostPath mounts unless explicitly required.
- Keep secrets out of plain manifests and source code.

## Configuration
- Keep configuration externalized.
- Validate configuration on startup and fail fast on invalid required values.
- Separate configuration from secrets.
- Do not hardcode environment-specific endpoints, credentials, or database DSNs.

## Networking and traffic
- Keep Services simple and explicit.
- Be clear about ports, health endpoints, and protocol expectations.
- Do not expose admin-only endpoints publicly.
- Use ingress or gateway configuration consistently with platform standards.

## Observability
- Emit structured logs to stdout/stderr.
- Expose health endpoints intentionally.
- Expose metrics endpoints only when required and secured appropriately.
- Ensure request IDs and trace context can flow through the service.

## Storage and filesystem
- Treat containers as ephemeral by default.
- Do not write required persistent state to local container filesystem.
- Use read-only root filesystem where practical.
- Write temporary files only when necessary and to explicit writable paths.

## Manifest hygiene
- Pin image versions intentionally.
- Do not use :latest in production.
- Keep labels, selectors, and annotations consistent.
- Do not change selectors casually.
- Keep manifests small, explicit, and easy to diff.